<font color="#FF0000">VETS AGAINST THE WAR</font><br>
<tt>Thu Dec  5 22:48:07 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I too was a Vietnam vet, yet I ended up protesting the war. I too had been raised in the tradition of John Wayne and firmly believed that if it hadn't been for the &quot;Duke&quot; we'd all be living in teepees and speaking Japanese.  However, as the son of a WWII vet I was also raised with the belief that war is hell and not something to be prolonged.  I was raised in the tradition of getting in, getting the job done, and getting out.  My military upbringing was goal oriented and the goal of any military action is the swift and utter defeat of the enemy.<br><br>
My disenchantment with the war in Vietnam came from the seeming inability of our political leaders to commit our vast arsenal of democracy to the defeat of the enemy of peace-loving peoples in the world.  When the war had been going on for some time and Pres. Johnson declared that it could and would likely last for another 10 years, at least, it didn't take a rocket scientist to realize that the committment of our political leaders left much to be desired.  I could not conceive of how it would take 10 years to subdue and defeat the tiny rag-tag military of North Vietnam.<br><br>
So, yes, I protested the war.  I took up what was perhaps the most sane rallying cry of the time, &quot;Get it done or get the hell out&quot;. <br><br>
My major regrets are that so many lives were lost before our esteemed leaders admitted that they had neither the heart nor the stomach to win the war and that the people of South Vietnam will forever remain people without a country.  Even if our vets did not receive a heros welcome when they returned home, there was still a home to which they could return. Not so for the South Vietnamese. 
<p><code>--   (Paul) </code><p>


